What are the differences between cache-first vs network-first strategies? How do you handle cache invalidation?

## Why This Is Asked
Broadcom needs engineers who can build robust real-time systems that work offline and handle network failures gracefully.

## Expected Answer
A strong candidate would discuss:
- Service worker caching strategies (network-first for API, cache-first for assets)
- IndexedDB for offline document storage
- WebSocket connection management with exponential backoff
- Conflict resolution using Operational Transform or CRDTs
- Background sync API for automatic data upload

## Code Example
```javascript
// Service worker with offline sync
self.addEventListener('sync', (event) => {
  if (event.tag === 'document-sync') {
    event.waitUntil(syncDocuments());
  }
});

async function syncDocuments() {
  const docs = await getOfflineDocuments();
  for (const doc of docs) {
    try {
      await fetch('/api/sync', {
        method: 'POST',
        body: JSON.stringify(doc)
      });
      await removeOfflineDoc(doc.id);
    } catch (err) {
      // Retry on next sync
      throw err;
    }
  }
}

// WebSocket reconnection with exponential backoff
class WebSocketManager {
  constructor(url) {
    this.url = url;
    this.reconnectAttempts = 0;
    this.maxReconnectAttempts = 5;
    this.baseDelay = 1000;
  }

  connect() {
    this.ws = new WebSocket(this.url);
    this.ws.onclose = () => this.handleReconnect();
  }

  handleReconnect() {
    if (this.reconnectAttempts < this.maxReconnectAttempts) {
      const delay = this.baseDelay * Math.pow(2, this.reconnectAttempts);
      setTimeout(() => {
        this.reconnectAttempts++;
        this.connect();
      }, delay);
    }
  }
}
```
